                correctAnswer: 'The remaining work (story points or tasks) versus time in a sprint or release',
                explanation: 'A Burndown Chart has time on the X-axis and remaining work (story points/tasks) on the Y-axis. The ideal line slopes down from total sprint points to zero at the end. A flat line means no progress; a line above the ideal means the team is behind; a line below means ahead. It gives an at-a-glance view of sprint health. A Burnup Chart (opposite) shows completed work rising toward total scope — better at showing scope creep.',
