                correctAnswer: 'The component renders `new Date()` on the server (at request time) and on the client (at hydration time, slightly later) — the values differ. Fix: use `suppressHydrationWarning` on the element OR render the date only client-side with `useEffect`',
                explanation: 'Hydration mismatch: React expects the client-rendered HTML to EXACTLY match the server-rendered HTML. `new Date()` on the server returns the time of the server request; `new Date()` on the client during hydration returns a slightly later time — mismatch. Solutions: (1) **`suppressHydrationWarning={true}`** on the element: `<time suppressHydrationWarning>{new Date().toLocaleTimeString()}</time>` — suppresses the warning, client renders its value; (2) **useEffect for client-only rendering**: `const [time, setTime] = useState(null); useEffect(() => setTime(new Date()), [])` — server renders null, client updates after mount; (3) **Time from props**: Pass the server time as a static prop and format on client. Common hydration mismatch causes: dates, random numbers, window-dependent values, browser extensions injecting content, improper HTML nesting (`<p>` inside `<p>`).',
