                correctAnswer: 'Option B for routing/redirects (fast, before page renders) + Option A for fine-grained data authorization — defense in depth',
                explanation: 'Defense in depth is the correct auth pattern: **Middleware (Option B)**: Runs at the Edge before the page renders. Best for: redirect unauthorized users before any server work happens (`redirect("/upgrade")`). Limitation: Edge Runtime has limited API access — typically checks cookies/JWTs but cannot call your database. **Server Component (Option A)**: Runs on the server, can call the database. Best for: fine-grained checks ("does this user own this specific resource?") and filtering data based on subscription. **Client check (Option C)**: Never rely on this for security — the server already sent the page; client is untrustworthy. The combination: Middleware catches 99% of unauthorized access fast (before any DB calls), Server Component catches edge cases the middleware JWT couldn\'t verify (e.g., subscription was cancelled after JWT was issued). Never trust client-side authorization alone.',
