                explanation: 'k-fold cross-validation: (1) Divide dataset into k equal folds (typically k=5 or k=10); (2) Iteration 1: train on folds 2-5, validate on fold 1; (3) Iteration 2: train on folds 1,3-5, validate on fold 2; ... (k) Iteration k: validate on fold k; (4) Average the k validation scores. Benefits: (1) Every data point is used for validation exactly once; (2) More reliable estimate than a single split (reduces variance of the score); (3) Critical for small datasets where a single unlucky split could be misleading. After k-fold evaluation, the final model is typically retrained on ALL data. Common variant: Stratified k-fold (preserves class distribution in each fold).',
