                explanation: 'A jump from 0.82 to 0.97 from one feature is a major red flag for **target leakage** (data leakage). Leakage occurs when features contain information about the future target that wouldn\'t be available at real prediction time. Example: if you\'re predicting "will this customer churn in the next 30 days" and "days_since_last_purchase" is calculated at the END of the 30-day window, it already encodes the answer (customers who churned have very high days_since). At prediction time, you only know past behavior. Types of leakage: (1) **Feature leakage**: feature computed using post-target data; (2) **Pipeline leakage**: normalizing/scaling before splitting (uses test statistics in training). Fix: carefully audit the temporal ordering of all features. Use time-aware feature computation: only use data available at the prediction timestamp. Re-split, recompute features correctly, re-evaluate.',
