                correctAnswer: 'Gradients shrinking exponentially as they propagate backward through many layers, making early layers learn very slowly — solved by residual connections (ResNet skip connections)',
                explanation: 'Vanishing gradient: when gradients are backpropagated through many layers, each multiplication by a weight matrix and derivative of sigmoid (<0.25) shrinks the gradient exponentially. Early layers receive near-zero gradients and barely learn. Solutions: (1) **ReLU activation**: derivative is 1 for positive inputs (no shrinking); (2) **Residual connections (ResNet)**: F(x) + x — the skip connection creates a "gradient highway" that bypasses layers, allowing gradients to flow unchanged to early layers. He et al. used this to train 152-layer networks; (3) **LSTM gates**: designed to prevent vanishing gradient in RNNs; (4) **Batch normalization**: stabilizes gradient magnitudes. The **exploding gradient** (opposite problem) is handled by gradient clipping.',
