                explanation: 'This is **distribution shift** / **dataset bias** — among the most dangerous failure modes for safety-critical ML. The model perfectly memorized the clear-weather distribution but the real world has fog, rain, night, glare. Key insight: **high test accuracy on a biased test set is misleading** — the test set must represent the deployment distribution. Solutions: (1) **Diverse data collection**: actively seek edge cases, adverse conditions (rain simulation, fog augmentation, GAN-generated weather); (2) **Domain randomization**: add synthetic weather augmentation during training; (3) **OOD detection**: the model should output "I\'m uncertain" for OOD inputs rather than making confident wrong predictions (use ensemble uncertainty, Monte Carlo Dropout); (4) **Subgroup evaluation**: evaluate separately on clear/rain/fog/night before deploying; (5) **Continuous monitoring**: detect distribution shift in production telemetry.',
