                correctAnswer: 'DP is built on multi-threading (single process), which is bottlenecked by Python\'s Global Interpreter Lock (GIL) and incurs heavy synchronization overhead; DDP spawns a separate, independent OS process per GPU, avoiding GIL bottlenecks and using highly optimized ring-allreduce communication.',
                explanation: '`torch.nn.DataParallel` (DP) uses a single-process, multi-threaded architecture. Because of Python\'s Global Interpreter Lock (GIL), only one thread can execute bytecode at a time, creating a major performance bottleneck. Furthermore, DP replicates the model weights on every forward pass, and the master GPU gathers all outputs and computes gradients, creating a severe bottleneck on GPU 0. In contrast, `DistributedDataParallel` (DDP) spawns one independent Python process per GPU (multi-process). There is no GIL bottleneck. The model is replicated only once at startup. Each process performs its own forward and backward passes on its slice of data, and gradients are averaged across GPUs asynchronously using highly optimized collective communication libraries (like NVIDIA\'s NCCL) using a ring-allreduce pattern. DDP scales near-linearly across hundreds of GPUs.',
                points: 3,
