                explanation: 'TF-IDF vector magnitudes reflect document length — a very long document repeating the same topic will have much larger vector coordinates than a short, concise article on the same topic. **Euclidean Distance** measures the straight-line distance between vector tips. Because of document length differences, the Euclidean distance between these two articles will be huge, indicating high dissimilarity. **Cosine Similarity** measures the cosine of the angle between the vectors: $\\cos(\\theta) = \\frac{A \\cdot B}{\\|A\\| \\|B\\|}$. This entirely discounts vector length (magnitude normalization), measuring purely the direction of the vector (relative word distributions). Thus, it correctly flags them as highly similar.',
