                explanation: 'Both pooling methods are used to downsample feature maps, reducing spatial dimensions (and parameter counts) while providing translation invariance. **Max Pooling** selects the maximum value in a window (e.g., 2x2 with stride 2). This is highly effective for sparse feature detection, capturing the most prominent visual features (e.g. "is there an edge here?"). **Average Pooling** computes the average of the values in the window. It retains more of the background context but can wash out strong individual activations. In modern networks, Max Pooling is preferred in intermediate convolutional layers to retain sharp features, while Global Average Pooling is often used right before the final classification layer to aggregate features across the entire spatial dimension.',
