                explanation: 'This is the classic extreme class imbalance problem in industrial CV where supervised learning completely fails. Duplicating 10 defect images (via SMOTE or oversampling) leads to severe overfitting, as the model memorizes the specific 10 defects (e.g. dust, specific scratches) and fails to detect new, unseen defect types. **Unsupervised Anomaly Detection** is the standard solution: (1) Train an **Autoencoder** (or U-Net structure) solely on the "normal" (non-defective) panel images. The model learns to compress and perfectly reconstruct normal panel patterns (grid lines, smooth textures); (2) When a defective panel (e.g., crack, hot spot) is fed in, the autoencoder fails to reconstruct the crack because it has never seen one. The output will have high reconstruction error (MSE) at the crack location; (3) By thresholding the reconstruction error, you can flag any panel with an error above $\\tau$ as defective. This detects completely novel defect types.',
