                correctAnswer: 'Deploy the model across two 80GB NVIDIA A100 GPUs using Tensor Parallelism (splitting matrix multiplications). Use a high-performance serving framework (like vLLM) that implements PagedAttention to prevent KV cache fragmentation, continuous batching (iteration-level scheduling) to group concurrent requests, and AWQ/GPTQ 4-bit weight quantization to reduce VRAM requirements to ~40GB.',
                explanation: 'Serving a 70B parameter LLM at scale requires a multi-faceted optimization: (1) **Weight Quantization (AWQ/GPTQ)**: in float16, the model requires 140GB of VRAM just to load. By quantizing to 4-bit, VRAM is reduced to ~40GB, allowing it to easily fit on a single or dual GPU while accelerating VRAM reading speeds; (2) **Tensor Parallelism**: splits massive matrix multiplications (like attention projections) across multiple GPUs (e.g., 2 GPUs via Megatron-LM), computing steps in parallel; (3) **PagedAttention**: in autoregressive generation, the **Key-Value (KV) Cache** stores previous tokens\' key-value matrices to avoid recalculation. The KV cache grows dynamically, causing massive VRAM fragmentation and allocation waste (often up to 60-80% VRAM lost). PagedAttention (implemented in vLLM) segments the KV cache into fixed-size virtual pages, similar to virtual memory in operating systems, reducing VRAM waste to near 0% and allowing 10x higher batch sizes; (4) **Continuous Batching**: traditional batching waits for all requests to finish generation. Since different requests generate different token lengths, this causes huge idle GPU time. Continuous batching batches requests at the *iteration level* (running a forward step for new requests alongside existing ones), increasing throughput by 3-5x. A naive PyTorch FastAPI deployment will quickly trigger OOMs and suffer from extremely high latency under concurrency.',
