                explanation: 'Traditional concatenative synthesis sounds highly robotic and lacks expressiveness. Mapping mel-spectrograms directly using older models (like Tacotron) struggles with voice cloning and pronunciation stability. **Modern generative audio** uses discrete tokenization: (1) **Neural Audio Codec** (EnCodec, SoundStream): uses an encoder-decoder with Residual Vector Quantization (RVQ) to compress raw continuous audio waveforms into a matrix of discrete integers (acoustic tokens) at a very low bitrate, while retaining rich acoustic details; (2) **Autoregressive Acoustic Model**: treats audio generation as a language modeling task (e.g. VALL-E, Bark). A Transformer is prompted with the target text (converted to phonemes) and the 10-second reference voice tokens. It models the joint probability of the text and predicts the sequence of target acoustic tokens; (3) **Neural Vocoder**: decodes the predicted acoustic tokens back into high-fidelity continuous 24kHz/44kHz waveform audio. By modeling speech using discrete tokens and self-attention, the system captures complex prosody, emotional tone, and speaker identity (voice cloning) exceptionally well.',
