                correctAnswer: 'Strides are the number of bytes to step in each dimension to find the next element. C-contiguous stores rows sequentially in memory; Fortran-contiguous stores columns sequentially. Flattening a C-contiguous array with reshape or ravel requires zero memory copy (returns a view), whereas doing so on a non-contiguous slice may trigger an expensive memory copy.',
                explanation: 'NumPy arrays use a contiguous block of flat memory. **Strides** are a tuple defining how many bytes to skip in memory to advance by 1 element along each axis. For an `int64` (8 bytes) array of shape `(3, 4)`: (1) In a **C-contiguous layout** (row-major order, standard C/C++), rows are stored sequentially: strides are `(32, 8)` (need 32 bytes to move down a row, 8 bytes to move across a column); (2) In a **Fortran-contiguous layout** (column-major order, standard Fortran/R), columns are stored sequentially: strides are `(8, 24)`. When you flatten a C-contiguous array using `.ravel()` or `.reshape(-1)`, NumPy simply updates the strides and shape metadata, returning a **view** in O(1) time without copying memory. However, if you attempt to flatten a sliced column array or a transposed array (which is non-contiguous), NumPy can no longer represent it as a single constant stride, forcing it to copy the data into a new memory block, incurring O(N) memory allocation and copy lag.',
