                explanation: 'In time-series modeling, the most dangerous error is **look-ahead bias** (data leakage). This occurs when a feature at time $t$ incorporates information from time $t+k$. For example, a rolling average centered at $t$ uses data from $t-15$ to $t+15$. If your model uses this centered average to predict prices at $t+5$, it has already seen the price of $t+15$ during training, yielding near-perfect training scores but crashing in production because future data is not available. **Prevention**: (1) Use only **lagged/backward-looking** windows: `df["feature"].shift(5)` or `rolling(30, closed="left")`; (2) **Time-Series Split**: never use standard random K-Fold cross-validation, as it leaks future data into the past. Use `TimeSeriesSplit` where the training set only contains data chronological prior to the validation set; (3) Ensure all aggregations and scaling parameter fits respect the time boundary.',
