                explanation: 'Selecting a **Shard Key** determines the scalability of a distributed database. (1) **Prevent Hotspots**: sharding by a timestamp (e.g. `Trans_Date`) will write all active transactions to the *current day\'s* shard, overloading that single node while the other 9 nodes sit idle. Sharding by `hash(UserID)` hashes the user ID, routing users randomly and evenly across all 10 shards, balancing the write load; (2) **Colocate Data**: if `UserTransactions`, `UserProfiles`, and `UserPosts` all use the same shard key (`UserID`), the database engine routing coordinator will place all records for a given user onto the **same physical node**. When a user logs in and queries their feed, profile, and history, the coordinator can fetch all data from a single shard in milliseconds. If they were sharded by different keys, the coordinator would have to perform a highly slow, distributed "scatter-gather" query across all 10 shards, creating a huge network bottleneck.',
