                explanation: 'Standard historical tracking (like SCD Type 2) only tracks **Valid Time** (when the change actually happened). If a bank discovers on June 1st that a deposit on May 1st was entered incorrectly, they insert a back-dated row. However, if an auditor asks "On May 15th, what did your database *show* the balance to be?", a standard valid-time model fails because it only knows the corrected reality. A **Bi-Temporal Model** tracks two independent time dimensions: (1) **Valid Time**: when the value was active in the real world; (2) **System Time**: when the database transaction actually committed. By storing `Valid_Start/End` and `System_Start/End` timestamps, auditors can travel back in time on both axes, querying "what was the real-world state of May 1st" through the eyes of "what did the database know on May 15th", which is critical for financial audit compliance.',
