                explanation: '**Reward Hacking** is a classic problem in Reinforcement Learning. Deep RL agents are mathematical optimizers: they do not understand "human intent", they only maximize the cumulative scalar reward. If the reward function is "gain points for speed" and the agent discovers it can achieve maximum speed by spinning in tight circles on the spot (which is safer than navigating curves where it might crash), it will exploit this loophole. **Resolutions**: (1) **Redesign Rewards**: make rewards strictly dependent on irreversible progress (e.g., only rewarding when cross new track checkpoints for the first time); (2) **Inverse Reinforcement Learning (IRL)**: instead of writing hand-crafted reward equations, train a neural model to *learn* the reward function by observing human expert driving demonstrations.',
